Reference-contexts: One approach to error recovery then is to split the TCP connection at these pivot points. One instance of TCP executes over each wired part while either another instance of TCP or a special purpose transport layer protocol executes over each wireless part <ref> [51, 5] </ref>. These protocol instances are bridged by a software agent at each pivot point that transforms between the different protocol semantics and formats if required. By isolating each protocol instance over a more homogeneous path, losses at problematic paths do not trigger end-to-end recovery. <p> Even when TCP is used over the wireless links, it can recover faster due to the shorter paths involved. Alternatively, the transport protocol used over the wireless links may employ more appropriate mechanisms such as SR, further enhancing performance <ref> [51] </ref>. Transport protocol semantics with this approach are between pivot points rather than end-to-end, since an acknowledgment does not mean correct reception at the eventual destination, only correct reception at the next pivot point. <p> This coupling between layers is thus required to solve an isolated and localized problem, with more end-to-end fixes needed in the future. Finally, they are only applicable to TCP. Split (or indirect ) TCP approaches <ref> [5, 51] </ref> deal with both mobility and link errors at the same time, but they require modifications both at the endpoints and at the pivot points, which are generally not under user control.
