Reference-contexts: Since these characteristics violate the assumptions that are commonly made for wired media, link layer protocols specialized for satellite links have been developed. These protocols are more sophisticated and complex than the ones used on the wired part of the Internet <ref> [52, 34] </ref>. Since IP, which is the lowest layer protocol that is common across the Internet, can execute on top of any link layer, this solution hides some of the unpleasant characteristics of satellite links from protocol layers above IP. <p> In this case if any frames have been transmitted that would not fit in the receiver's buffer, they can be assumed lost and retransmitted immediately in hopes that the receiver will recover from previous losses in the meantime <ref> [52] </ref>. Buffer overflow can also occur when multiple return frames are lost, whether ACK or NAK, since the sender will keep transmitting frames until its buffer is filled, and then stall until a timeout occurs.
